/***************************************************************************************************/
/**********     CHOOSE THE HYPOTHESIS TEST: WILCOXON RANK SUM (A.K.A. MANN-WHITNEY U)  *************/
/***************************************************************************************************/


/************************************************************************/
/**********      BEGINNING: HYPOTHESIS TEST        *********************/
/************************************************************************/
/* YOU CAN ONLY USE THE EXACT WILCOXON ON SMALL SAMPLE SIZES. See notes at the end of this section. */
/* I WANT YOU TO USE THE CONTINUITY CORRECTION FACTOR SO USE CORRECT=YES */

ods graphics on / outputfmt=static;
PROC NPAR1WAY DATA = work.bike WILCOXON CORRECT=YES;
  CLASS 'Holiday Status'n;
  VAR 'Casual Rentals'n;
RUN;
ods graphics off;
/* Wilcoxon Statistic: 	
	S = 8740.5. The sum of the ranks of the casual bike rentals for “Holiday” are 8740.5 rentals.

z-value: 			
	Z = 1.052. The Wilcoxon test statistic is 1.052 standard deviations to the right of the 
	hypothesized sum of ranks of 7686 rentals.
	
p-value: 			
	p-value = 0.2691. There is a 27% chance of observing a sum of ranks for the 
	smallest sample (Holiday) of 8740.5 or less or 6631.5 or more. 
	This is consistent with what would be expected under the assumption of no difference in medians.

Conclusion: 		
	Since our p-value (0.2691) is greater than our significance level (0.05), 
	we are 95% confident that we cannot reject the null hypothesis and 
	cannot say that the median Casual Bike Rentals for Holiday and Not a Holiday are different.
 */

/************************************************************************/
/**********      END: HYPOTHESIS TEST        *********************/
/************************************************************************/

/************************************************************************/
/**********      NO POST HOC        *********************/

/* Compute the best that we have post hoc. 
There is no post hoc procedure for Wilcoxon Rank Sum Test. 

It would be a confidence interval on the difference ot the two medians.  

As a "best that we have for a post hoc," divide the data into two datasets: 
one for holidays and one for not holidays.
 
Use the confidence interval on median using the sign test post hoc 
"confidence interval on percentile distribution free 
(cipctdf)" to see if the confidence intervals overlap. */

Proc Univariate data=WORK.bike cipctldf alpha=.05;
  CLASS 'Holiday Status'n;
  VAR 'Casual Rentals'n;
Run;
/* Since 50% of the population of Casual Rentals for Not a Holiday is between 668 to 758, 
the confidence interval of Casual Rentals for Holiday (440 to 1514) is within the confidence 
interval for Not a Holiday. Because of this, it looks like there is a significant difference 
between the two groups, Holiday and Not a Holiday. */

